"attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire):","topographic name from the Swale river in North Yorkshire, the name of which probably derives from Old English <i>swalwe</i> ‘whirlpool or rushing water’.","alternatively, perhaps from the Middle English female personal name <i>Swale</i>, Old Norse <i>Svala</i>, from <i>svala</i> ‘swallow’ (the bird)."],"variants":[{"name":"Swales","meanings":["English (North and Yorkshire): variant of   Swale  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Swale had at least 1 son with Olina Bolour."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1300":"1300","about 1300":"umbes 1300","Fremington, Yorkshire, England":"Fremington, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1300":"1300","about 1300":"noin 1300","Fremington, Yorkshire, England":"Fremingt